external_knowledge:
- 'Smith' refers to the last name of the researcher;
- '2023' refers to the year the experiment was conducted;
- 'growth yield' is a measurement of the growth of the sample in the experiment.

- 'Garden of scientific exploration' refers to the database where experiments are conducted;
- 'Plants' refer to the phenotype records;
- 'Biologists' refer to researchers in the Biology department;
- 'Plot' refers to the experiment;
- 'More than one plant' means the experiment has more than one phenotype record.

- "phenotypic data" includes growth yield, generation time, population doublings, and colony size after 48 hours;
- "sample origins" refer to the organism type, sample source, collection date, strain ID, genotype, and storage location;
- "treatment details" encompass the type, duration, concentration, protocol, and control group status;
- "research findings" include the summary, conclusion, data analysis methods, and statistical significance;
- "scientists' contributions" are represented by the researchers' IDs, first names, last names, emails, departments, and titles;
- "event logs" capture the types of events, descriptions, dates, timestamps, and user IDs associated with each experiment.

- "phenotype records" refer to unique identifiers for each phenotype observation in a biological experiment;
- "top 10" means the experiments with the highest counts of phenotype records;
- "researcher involved" includes the researcher's full name (first name and last name) and department.

- "seasoned gardener" refers to the researcher with `researcher_id = 1`;
- "crops in the experimental fields" refers to the samples in the experiments;
- "growth yield" is a measure of how well the samples have grown.

- "seeds sown by John Doe" refers to experiments conducted by the researcher named John Doe;
- "garden" is a metaphor for the experimental setup or laboratory where the experiments are conducted;
- "dawn of the new year in 2022 until the last day of 2023" refers to the date range from January 1, 2022, to December 31, 2023;
- "beds" are metaphorical for the experiments;
- "more than one type of seed was planted" means that each experiment has at least two phenotypes associated with it.

- 'Fiery touch of heat shock' refers to the experimental condition where plants are exposed to heat shock treatment;
- 'More than one recorded measurement of its growth' means the experiment has multiple phenotype records;
- 'Average growth yield' is the mean value of the growth yield measurements for each experiment.

- "Completed experiments" refer to experiments whose status is marked as 'Completed' in the database;
- "Recorded phenotypes" are the unique phenotype records associated with each experiment;
- "Top 3 researchers" are those who have conducted the experiments with the highest number of recorded phenotypes.

- "cumulative growth yield" refers to the total growth yield accumulated over time for each experiment;
- "mature over time" refers to the progression of the experiment, with `collection_date` indicating the time points at which samples were collected;
- "recorded in each experiment" means the data is grouped by `experiment_id` and ordered by `experiment_date` and `collection_date`.

- "effective treatments" refers to treatments with the highest average growth yield;
- "nurtured the most robust growth" refers to the highest average growth yield;
- "garden of experiments" is a metaphor for the set of experiments conducted;
- "blossoms" refers to the growth yield measurements.

- 'cumulative growth yield' is the sum of growth yields for each sample up to the current generation time;
- 'cumulative generation time' is the sum of generation times for each sample up to the current generation time;
- 'rank' is based on the cumulative generation time, with lower ranks indicating earlier cumulative generation times.

- "cumulative growth yield" refers to the sum of growth yield measurements for a strain within an experiment up to the current strain ID;
- "greater than 0.5" is a threshold used to filter strains with significant growth;
- "experiments" involve multiple treatments and samples, and the growth yield is a measure of how well the strains grow under these conditions.

- 'Top 3' refers to the experiments with the lowest p-values (statistical significance) within each department;
- 'Completed' status indicates that the experiments have been finished and their results are finalized;
- 'Statistical significance' is a measure of the reliability of the experiment's results, with a lower value indicating more significant results.
